rkflow source bytes, metadata, requirements, and content hashes — never secret values."],[39,"Agent consumers — point AI agents at your Hub."],[40,"Agents, Skills & Knowledge"],[944,"Aliases are the same registry entries registered twice, so they always share\nthe canonical route's handler, auth, and scopes; in `openapi.json` each alias\ncarries `x-canonical-path`. Unversioned `/api/...` paths remain fully\nsupported — use whichever reads better. The legacy `/api/capabilities/*`\npaths are deprecated aliases of `/api/workflows/*` and get no `/api/v1` form;\nnew clients should say *workflow* everywhere."],[220,"All boards, default first."],[55,"All three are versioned and can be individually enabled/disabled."],[46,"Alongside workflows, the Hub maintains a shared catalog of reusable building blocks. They live in the database, are readable by any authenticated token, and are edited only by admins — so every workflow on the Hub draws from the same curated set."],[95,"An **approval** is a declared question with a declared consequence, presented to a human as a card in the web app, over Telegram, or through the API/MCP. Cards can hold a run before it executes (`waiting_approval`), pause a workflow mid-run at an engine gate, or simply record a decision. A run held on an approval waits indefinitely — waiting never fails it."],[1058,"An approval is a declared question with a declared consequence. Cards carry an *ask* — who is asked, what approving does, and why a human is needed — and every surface renders that stored ask verbatim. A run held on a card sits in `waiting_approval` and is never failed or age-reaped for waiting."],[111,"An ask without both `action` and `reason` is treated as absent; such cards fall back to a heuristic ask explicitly marked `derived: true`, so a guessed question is never presented as an authored one."],[398,"An invalid budget is rejected with `400 budget_invalid` at creation (and surfaces as a preflight blocker in negotiation) — a requested cap 