"The CLI stores named remotes (Hub URL + token) in `~/.runyard/config.json`\n(mode `0600`). Every command accepts global options `--url`, `--token`,\n`--remote <name>`, and `--json` (machine-readable output)."],[399,"The CLI takes budgets as flags: `runyard run research --max-tokens 200000 --max-cost 2` (`--max-cost` is US dollars; the same flags work on `runyard preflight`)."],[872,"The complete MCP tool set (parity-tested against the API surface). Connect with `runyard mcp install` or the `runyard-mcp` stdio server."],[1524,"The corresponding MCP tools are `get_workflow_source`, `list_workflow_bundles`, and `get_workflow_bundle` (which does include the source). You can also publish a bundle directly with `POST /api/workflow-bundles` / `publish_workflow_bundle` and reference it by `workflow.bundleId`, but prefer inline source — the Hub publishes the bundle for you."],[106,"The creator of a card states the ask up front, and every surface renders it verbatim:"],[1278,"The current saved remote"],[1083,"The decision is applied to the paused workflow on the runner and it resumes past the gate."],[595,"The encrypted secret store - admin-managed, listable by name only, delivered to runs at claim time and never returned by the API."],[214,"The example factory board leaves a **documented but unwired** hook point for release-notes and social automation: the natural place is a lane trigger on `shipped` that runs a `docs-update` or `release-notes` workflow, plus a schedule entry (e.g. cron `0 15 * * FRI`) that posts a weekly digest. Wiring Twitter or another network is a matter of adding the corresponding secret, a hook profile that consumes it, and a workflow that reads the run's artifacts — none of which this template ships, because the credentials must be operator-provided."],[1158,"The example ships in the repo at `workflow-templates/board-definitions/runyard-development-factory.json` and is fetchable over the API too. YAML is a future syntax; JSON is the documented format